[[File:Kada-kasuga-jinja honden.jpg|thumb|200px|Honden (National Important Cultural Property)]]
'''Kada Kasuga Shrine''' (加太春日神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in {{ill|Kada, Wakayama City|ja|和歌山市加太}}, {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県}}, Japan. It holds historical and cultural significance as a former {{ill|Mura-sha|ja|村社}}.

== Deities ==
; Primary deities
* {{ill|Ame-no-Koyane|ja|天児屋根命}}
* {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕槌神}}
* {{ill|Futsunushi|ja|経津主神}}

; Additional deities
* {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神}}
* {{ill|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|ja|住吉大神}}

== History ==
The shrine's foundation is uncertain, but according to records from the {{ill|Kii-no-Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|紀国造}}, the shrine dates back to the {{ill|Jimmu period|ja|神武天皇}}. It is said that Tendo-ne-no-Mikoto, ancestor of the Kii-no-Kuni clan, carried the sacred treasures—the {{ill|Divine Mirror|ja|神鏡}} and the {{ill|Sun Spear|ja|日矛}}—to Kada Bay, where a temporary palace was constructed to enshrine {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大御神}}. These treasures were later venerated as the sacred objects of {{ill|Hichimen Shrine|ja|日前神宮・国懸神宮}}.

Although not listed in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式}}, the shrine is mentioned in the {{ill|Kii-no-Kuni Shrine Register|ja|紀伊国神名帳}} as "Shoichii Kasuga Daimyojin" (正一位春日大神). During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代}}, the legendary ascetic {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役小角}} used {{ill|Tomogashima Island|ja|友ヶ島}} as a sacred training ground and enshrined the shrine's guardian deity there. As a result, the shrine remains connected to the practices of the {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道}} tradition.

In later years, due to the area's prominence as a fishing village along the {{ill|Kitan Strait|ja|紀淡海峡}}, the shrine began to include {{ill|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|ja|住吉大神}} as a deity for maritime safety and abundant catches. During the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代}}, it became known as "Sumiyoshi Shrine." Historical documents, such as a 1317 land dedication from the Mukai family archives, refer to the shrine as "Kada Manor Sumiyoshi Shrine."

In the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代}}, Fujiwara descendants introduced the {{ill|Kasuga deities|ja|春日三神}}, naming the shrine "Kasuga Shrine." Historical records such as the "Kasuga Myojin Festival Diary" (1442) affirm this name.

The shrine's current location is due to relocation ordered by {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉}}’s vassal {{ill|Kuwahara Shigeharu|ja|桑山重晴}} during the {{ill|Tenshō period|ja|天正年間}}. Extensive reconstructions occurred in 1596, as evidenced by a {{ill|Ridge Tag|ja|棟札}}, now designated a National Important Cultural Property.

== Cultural Properties ==
=== Important Cultural Properties ===
* **Honden (Main Hall)**: Constructed in 1596, the one-bay {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造}} building is designated as a National Important Cultural Property (since December 14, 1931).<ref>{{National Cultural Property Database|102|2822|Kada Kasuga Shrine Main Hall}}</ref><ref>[http://wakayamacity-bunkazai.jp/shitei/784/ Kada Kasuga Shrine, Wakayama City Cultural Properties]</ref>

== References ==
{{reflist}}

== External Links ==
* [http://www.hir.ne.jp/e3/omiya/index.html Kada Kasuga Shrine Official Site] (in Japanese)

