'''Kada Kasuga Shrine''' (加太春日神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kada, Wakayama City|ja|和歌山市加太|12=draft}}, {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|12=draft}}, Japan. It holds historical and cultural significance as a former {{ill|Mura-sha|ja|村社|12=draft}}.

== Deities ==
; Primary deities
* {{ill|Ame-no-Koyane|ja|天児屋根命|1=Ame-no-Koyane|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕槌神|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Futsunushi|ja|経津主神|12=draft}}

; Additional deities
* {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|ja|住吉大神|12=draft}}

== History ==
The shrine's foundation is uncertain, but according to records from the {{ill|Kii-no-Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|紀国造|12=draft}}, the shrine dates back to the {{ill|Jimmu period|ja|神武天皇|12=draft}}. It is said that Tendo-ne-no-Mikoto, ancestor of the Kii-no-Kuni clan, carried the sacred treasures—the {{ill|Divine Mirror|ja|神鏡|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Sun Spear|ja|日矛|12=draft}}—to Kada Bay, where a temporary palace was constructed to enshrine {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大御神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=draft}}. These treasures were later venerated as the sacred objects of {{ill|Hichimen Shrine|ja|日前神宮・国懸神宮|12=draft}}.

Although not listed in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|12=draft}}, the shrine is mentioned in the {{ill|Kii-no-Kuni Shrine Register|ja|紀伊国神名帳|12=draft}} as "Shoichii Kasuga Daimyojin" (正一位春日大神). During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|12=draft}}, the legendary ascetic {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役小角|12=draft}} used {{ill|Tomogashima Island|ja|友ヶ島|12=draft}} as a sacred training ground and enshrined the shrine's guardian deity there. As a result, the shrine remains connected to the practices of the {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|12=draft}} tradition.

In later years, due to the area's prominence as a fishing village along the {{ill|Kitan Strait|ja|紀淡海峡|12=draft}}, the shrine began to include {{ill|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|ja|住吉大神|12=draft}} as a deity for maritime safety and abundant catches. During the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft}}, it became known as "Sumiyoshi Shrine." Historical documents, such as a 1317 land dedication from the Mukai family archives, refer to the shrine as "Kada Manor Sumiyoshi Shrine."

In the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft}}, Fujiwara descendants introduced the {{ill|Kasuga deities|ja|春日三神|12=draft}}, naming the shrine "Kasuga Shrine." Historical records such as the "Kasuga Myojin Festival Diary" (1442) affirm this name.

The shrine's current location is due to relocation ordered by {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft}}’s vassal {{ill|Kuwahara Shigeharu|ja|桑山重晴|12=draft}} during the {{ill|Tenshō period|ja|天正年間|12=draft}}. Extensive reconstructions occurred in 1596, as evidenced by a {{ill|Ridge Tag|ja|棟札|12=draft}}, now designated a National Important Cultural Property.

