* {{ill|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|ja|住吉大神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Sanjin|qq=}}

== History ==
The shrine's foundation is uncertain, but according to records from the {{ill|Kii-no-Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|紀国造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kii-no-Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}}, the shrine dates back to the {{ill|Jimmu period|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jimmu period|qq=}}. It is said that Tendo-ne-no-Mikoto, ancestor of the Kii-no-Kuni clan, carried the sacred treasures—the {{ill|Divine Mirror|ja|神鏡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Divine Mirror|qq=}} and the {{ill|Sun Spear|ja|日矛|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sun Spear|qq=}}—to Kada Bay, where a temporary palace was constructed to enshrine {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大御神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|qq=}}. These treasures were later venerated as the sacred objects of {{ill|Hichimen Shrine|ja|日前神宮・国懸神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hichimen Shrine|qq=}}.

Although not listed in the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki|qq=}}, the shrine is mentioned in the {{ill|Kii-no-Kuni Shrine Register|ja|紀伊国神名帳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kii-no-Kuni Shrine Register|qq=}} as "Shoichii Kasuga Daimyojin" (正一位春日大神). During the {{ill|Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asuka period|qq=}}, the legendary ascetic {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役小角|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/En no Gyōja|qq=}} used {{ill|Tomogashima Island|ja|友ヶ島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomogashima Island|qq=}} as a sacred training ground and enshrined the shrine's guardian deity there. As a result, the shrine remains connected to the practices of the {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shugendō|qq=}} tradition.

In later years, due to the area's prominence as a fishing village along the {{ill|Kitan Strait|ja|紀淡海峡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kitan Strait|qq=}}, the shrine began to include {{ill|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|ja|住吉大神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Sanjin|qq=}} as a deity for maritime safety and abundant catches. During the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}}, it became known as "Sumiyoshi Shrine." Historical documents, such as a 1317 land dedication from the Mukai family archives, refer to the shrine as "Kada Manor Sumiyoshi Shrine."

In the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}, Fujiwara descendants introduced the {{ill|Kasuga deities|ja|春日三神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kasuga deities|qq=}}, naming the shrine "Kasuga Shrine." Historical records such as the "Kasuga Myojin Festival Diary" (1442) affirm this name.

The shrine's current location is due to relocation ordered by {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=}}’s vassal {{ill|Kuwahara Shigeharu|ja|桑山重晴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuwahara Shigeharu|qq=}} during the {{ill|Tenshō period|ja|天正年間|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō period|qq=}}. Extensive reconstructions occurred in 1596, as evidenced by a {{ill|Ridge Tag|ja|棟札|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ridge Tag|qq=}}, now designated a National Important Cultural Property.

